===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{m|fro|monicion}}, {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|monicion}}, and their source, {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|monitio|monitiō|warning, admonition}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/məˈnɪʃn̩/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[caution]] or [[warning]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''1890''', [[w:Henry James|Henry James]], ''The Tragic Muse'':
#*: He cherished the usual wise '''monitions''', such as that one was not to make a fool of one's self and that one should not carry on one's technical experiments in public.
# A legal [[notification]] of something. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
# A [[sign]] of impending danger; an [[omen]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* '''1839''', {{w|Edgar Allan Poe}}, ‘William Wilson’:
#*: I recognise the first ambiguous '''monitions''' of the destiny which afterwards so fully overshadowed me.

